sceleri Oppianici, ‘to that scoundrel of an Oppianicus. Scelus was used colloquially as a term of reproach, and occurs frequently in the comic poets. Plautus also has scelus viri, ‘ you scoundrel of a fellow,’ scelus pueri, flaqitium hominis, etc. For a similar colloquialism in Cicero, cp. inire: so Baiter, Kayser, Ramsay, Miiller. There can be little doubt that this reading should be preferred to iniri (Classen, Faussett): the form of the sentence makes it probable that two similar infinitives were to stand at the beginning of each clause. The examples of a change of con- struction from passive to active, quoted by commentators, do not seem to be in point.
